TCP is connection-oriented and provides reliable communication using streams, 
while UDP is connectionless and uses packets with no guarantee of delivery, 
making it faster but less reliable.

TCP FLOW :  Each client → separate FD
            socket(AF_INET, SOCK_STREAM, 0);
            bind()
            listen()
            accept()
            send()
            recv()

Server:
socket()
  ↓
bind()
  ↓
listen()
  ↓
accept()  → new client FD
  ↓
recv() / send()

Client:
socket()
  ↓
connect()
  ↓
send() / recv()



UDP FLOW :  Single socket handles ALL clients
            Client identified by IP + PORT

            socket(AF_INET, SOCK_DGRAM, 0);
            bind()
            sendto()
            recvfrom()

Server:
socket()
  ↓
bind()
  ↓
recvfrom()
  ↓
sendto()

Client:
socket()
  ↓
sendto()
  ↓
recvfrom()